==Old English==
===Etymology===
From the Germanic, from Indo-European ''*dekṃ-'' ‘ten’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''tiān'', Old High German [[zehan]] (German [[zehn]]), Old Saxon [[tehan]] (Dutch [[tien]]), Old Norse ''tíu'' (Swedish [[tio]]), Gothic [[𐍄𐌰𐌹𐌷𐌿𐌽]]; and, outside the Germanic languages, with Sanskrit [[दश]], Greek [[δέκα]], Latin [[decem]], Old Irish [[deich]] (Irish [[deich]]).
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ti:en/
===Cardinal number===
'''tīen''' (ordinal: '''teoþa'''/'''teogoþa''')
# [[ten]], [[10]]
===Alternative spellings===
'''Tīen''' or '''tīene''' are West Saxon forms, also represented by Anglian '''tēn''' or '''tēne'''.

